I think so too @bernaferrari 

Currently there is a factory to create `ThemeData` from a `colorScheme` like this:
```dart
ThemeData.from(colorScheme: myColorScheme).copyWith(
    // Do your component specific theming here...
);
```

In my believe something like this could also be done for the new tokens like so:
```dart
ThemeData.from(tokens: myTokens).copyWith(
    // Do your component specific theming here...
);
```

`tokens` being something like a `Material3Tokens` class that can be initialized with JSON

I would be open to creating a PR implementing this in the future ... what do you think @rami-a

> ![Screenshot_1](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/102767277/184247641-c3dd3a1c-2591-4405-9455-b251d34be4d6.png) ![Screenshot_2](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/102767277/184247644-76ff0405-4079-40f0-a6c9-35d2948f33e3.png)
> 
> I noticed that these two buttons known as ElevatedButton in Material 3 style can only be implemented in a separate class, not in MyApp. Otherwise, they will look like the default.

This is desired behaviour, if you want to use Filled or Filled Tonal button styles, you have to create your own classes.
```dart
/// | Type         | Flutter implementation  |
/// | :----------- | :---------------------- |
/// | Elevated     | [ElevatedButton]        |
/// | Filled       | Styled [ElevatedButton] |
/// | Filled Tonal | Styled [ElevatedButton] |
/// | Outlined     | [OutlinedButton]        |
/// | Text         | [TextButton]            |
```

Check out examples [here](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/blob/master/examples/api/lib/material/button_style/button_style.0.dart).
